SIMPLE: lording
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lording
<hw>Lord"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Lord</ets> +
<ets>-ing</ets>, 3.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The son of a lord; a person
of noble lineage.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A little lord; a lordling; a lord, in contempt or
ridicule.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In the plural, a common ancient mode of address
equivalent to ⟦ldquo⟧Sirs⟦rdquo⟧ or ⟦ldquo⟧My masters.⟦rdquo⟧</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Therefore, <qex>lordings</qex> all, I you beseech.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lordkin</ent>⟦br⟧
